Static Methods in Interface

Interview Questions

1. Can an interface have static methods in Java 8?
-->Answer:

Yes.
Java 8 introduced static methods in interfaces.
They belong to the interface, not to its implementing classes.
Used to provide utility/helper methods.

Example:

interface Demo {

    static void show() {
        System.out.println("Static Method");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo.show();
    }
}







2. How do we call a static method of an interface?
-->Answer:
      
      Call it using the interface name.
      Syntax:
      InterfaceName.methodName();
      
      Example:
      
      interface Demo {
      
          static void display() {
              System.out.println("Hello");
          }
      }
      
      public class Main {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
              Demo.display();
          }
      }







3. Can static methods be inherited by implementing classes?
-->Answer:

      No.
      Static methods are not inherited.
      They can only be accessed using the interface name.
      
      Example:
      
      interface Demo {
      
          static void show() {
              System.out.println("Hello");
          }
      }
      
      class Test implements Demo { }
      
      public class Main {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
              Demo.show();      // Correct
              // Test.show();   // Compile-time Error
          }
      }



4. What is the purpose of static methods inside an interface?
-->
Provide utility/helper methods related to the interface.
Avoid creating separate utility classes.
Can be called without creating an object.





Programs

1. Create an interface with a static method and call it from the main method.
        interface Demo {
        
            static void greet() {
                System.out.println("Welcome");
            }
        }
        
        public class Main {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
        
                Demo.greet();
            }
        }
        
        Output:
        Welcome




2. Show what happens if a class defines the same static method name.
-->interface Demo {

    static void show() {
        System.out.println("Interface");
    }
}

class Test implements Demo {

    static void show() {
        System.out.println("Class");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Demo.show();
        Test.show();
    }
}

Output:

Interface
Class

Note: The class method does not override the interface's static method. Both methods are independent.

Interview Tips (Quick Revision)
Static methods in interfaces were introduced in Java 8.
Declared using the static keyword.
Called using the interface name (InterfaceName.method()).
Cannot be inherited or overridden by implementing classes.
Used for utility/helper methods related to the interface.
No object creation is required to call a static interface method.
